<h2>Usability of Web Photos</h2>
<p><strong><a href="http://www.fivesimplesteps.com/products/usability-of-web-photos" rel="external">Usability of Web Photos</a></strong> by James Chudley was the first of the second 5 Simple Steps collection that I read. </p>

<p>Images are one of the most prominent features of any website and a lot of consideration goes in to them with regards to performance but not as much, I find, into what the images actually are. </p>

<p>I’ve also been guilty of this in the past, and on a recent client site that will remain anonymous this definitely applies to the person responsible for some of the image choices there! </p>

<p>The further I got with this book (as with some of the others) the more guilty I felt of committing the crimes(!) that James mentions that can contribute towards poor usability when images are chosen to represent a product or service on a website and the more I read, the more it made sense and I wanted to implement some of his methods – and use his framework for choosing good photos.</p>


